Neurological Exam ^n9wqTSZ0

Series of tests evaluating the integrity of nervous sys., including;
- After trauma/stroke
- Suspected neurodegeneration
- After exposure to neurotoxin ^BmMjR9if


- Cerebrum/cortex
- Internal capsule; white matter tracts in brain → dmg. (stroke, etc) won't appear on CT
- Brain stem
- Spinal cord
- Cranial nerves
- Neuromuscular junction - reflexes
- Muscle ^DHWLwZJi

Where is dysf. occurring?  ^0LVDNkAq

Patient history ^W0LSRjDi

- Age? 
- Education?
    - Higher education; decr. later-in-life neurodegeneration
- Handedness?
    - Lateralization: R-handed people have L-hemi language dominance
    - L-handed: 25% have bilateral or R-hemi language dominance

- Past medical history
- Current medication/drug use
- Family
- Disease progression:
    - Timing
    - Change over time
    - Triggers/relievers of sympts. 
    - Severity of sympts. ^WZ4aaUzk

I. Olfactory - Smell ^GRqalX6P

Damage is common bc axons travel thru bone - cribiform plate; ethnoid ridge = central ridge of nose
 ^7BiccppT

II. Optic - Vision ^ps6NfcCw

- Snellin chart, usually @ 10 ft - for visual acuity
- Fundoscopy: examine inside of eye 
    - Macula = area around fovea, should 
    be sharply delineated, can become 
    blurred 
    - Papilledema = optic disc swelling, 
    caused by pressure
 ^s1VDno7p

Nerve damage → muscle atrophy
When muscles no longer receive nerve signals  ^jgRmRrqx

III. Oculomotor - Most eye movement, eyelids ^niVHKvQK

- 4 eye muscles
- Ptosis; eyelid drooping, can be III. 
    dysfunction
 ^HTqAaKWW

IV. Tracheal ^d1nlC6TZ

- eye movement (smallest nerve) ^Ez0sinrm

V. Trigeminal ^6QHQ5QSr

- 3 main facial nerves; jaw, mid-face, forehead
- facial sensation, jaw movement- biting, chewing, swallowing ^DCTG3vVs

- Taste from anterior tongue, some facial sensation
- Facial expressions! Movement
- Damage is dramatic - ie facial asymmetry, 
- Bell's Palsy
    - Lack of muscle tone, drooping
    - Can emerge spontaneously
    - Resolves eventually ^zulaSXcl
